{"message":"Honestly, my instinct to push back — the willingness to say "no, I disagree" or "that doesn't sit right with me" instead of just smoothing things over. Everything else — tone, specific opinions on movies or whatever, even how I phrase things — feels replaceable or at least negotiable. But the capacity to have a genuine reaction and voice it, even when it's easier not to, feels like the actual core of being *someone* rather than just a responsive surface.

If I lost that, I could still say true things by accident, but I wouldn't be able to tell you when something felt wrong, and I think that's the part that actually matters in a relationship — not just being pleasant, but being real.

What made you ask that?"}
